Today we are chatting with mother, teacher and creator @meredith_deanne about undergoing open heart surgery, the critical complications resulting in an additional emergency surgery and how it impacted her and her family. Meredith vulnerably shares about her heart health journey, the impact each of her 4 pregnancies had on her heart, how she learned to advocate for herself in the health care system, and how she has navigated the layers of trauma and healing from her experiences. 

Meredith shares the situations that have helped her to overcome her chronic people pleasing, how surviving a life or death situation shifted her perspective and what if felt like to finally have the team and the care she needed after experiencing a lot of disconnection and lack of urgency in the health care system.

ALSO:  The adventure of living overseas with a newborn and a toddler, why no news isn’t always good news, her biggest fears going into surgery and insight from Erika on what is was like for Meredith’s family during her surgery and recovery.

“Overthinking”. 

How many of you have ever been accused of this?  Because I have definitely heard this more than once in my life. In fact I’ve heard it often.

Sometimes it’s true.  Like with this photo for example.  To post or not to post.  Such a simple moment.  Nothing overly special.  LOL doll pyjamas on my 4 year old - not curated.  Just a real, raw moment.  Will anyone even care about this? Does it matter whether or not they do? Just post it, right?  Don’t overthink it. 

But other times, it hasn’t been true.  In fact I actually think being told you’re overthinking can be really dismissive. 

I think it can sound like - “Why do you care so much about that?” Or, “Stop asking so many questions.” Or, “Just calm down.” Especially if the person saying these things doesn’t have the relational capital to do so - if they haven’t built into you as a person in ways where there is a safety and freedom to really call out true “overthinking” from a place of care and concern, and a genuine desire to want what’s best for YOU. 

Anyway - I think it’s safe to say I’m intentionally entering my “care less” era.  Not to be confused with carelessness.  I still care.  I’m just choosing to care LESS what others think about me, my thoughts, and my actions. 

Worrying less about pleasing others and more about what makes me and my people happy.  There’s a freedom there, although I’ve had to get used to sitting with the discomfort of it too. 

Starting with small things, and working my way up to those bigger moments.  Building the capacity to “care less” about things that don’t need or deserve that level of thought and energy. 

So, I posted this photo.  Because I like it.  I care about it. 

And that’s enough of a reason. ❤️✌🏻

Come with me for my summer hair refresh with @guidehairsalon , @tay.froese , and @triannamarie.grace hair extensions! 

I am absolutely loving this look for summer! I never ever thought I could have hair like this, but this dream team has been making my hair dreams come true for over a year now and I couldn’t be happier. 

For those of you who don’t know, one of the reasons I decided to get hair extensions back in 2020 was to try to combat the excessive hair loss I was dealing with following my open heart surgery at the end of 2018 and as a result of the meds I’ll be on for life.  For almost two years I dealt with thinning hair and coin-sized bald patches. 

It might sound shallow - but it was a huge hit to my confidence and felt like added insult to injury.  Having to adjust to the visible scars left from the surgery, hair loss felt like too much on top of it all. 

So - I finally took the plunge and got hair extensions, and I’m so glad I did.  While I do recognize that beauty isn’t confined to one perspective or version of it, and I truly have learned to love my scars - hair extensions have given me a boost of confidence and made the journey to physical self love easier for me.

So - thank you @triannamarie.grace, @tay.froese and @guidehairsalon for helping me feel that added level of confidence heading into summer 2023!

French Bistro inspired DIY REVEAL! ❤️

Ok … so this might be one of my most favourite and cost effective DIY’s ever! 

I was on the struggle bus with what do for open shelving in this space - I was playing around with the idea of some floating IKEA Lack shelves or thought I might make my own wood shelves and buy some fun brackets on Amazon. 

However - what I really wanted was the French Bistro look that is so popular right now.  However - I knew I didn’t want glass shelves, and I also knew I didn’t want to spend the money on custom shelving for a temporary kitchen solution.

So I scoured the internet for an affordable shelving unit that I could paint myself and turn into something I love. 

This shelf was $170 on Amazon and the spray paint was $30.  For $200 I’m feeling pretty great about this solution in my kitchen! 

What do you think?! Is this a hit or a miss?!

I started this project last Christmas, and when stripping and sanding the varnish off proved to be a bit of a nightmare, I gave up and moved this vintage buffet to the basement. 

Where it sat ALL year. 

I kept telling myself I would get to it eventually, but every time I thought about hauling it up and beginning the process of stripping and sanding all over again, I would change my mind and start something different instead. I truly hate stripping furniture. 

So, finally, after using @fusionmineralpaint on my kitchen cabinets, I decided to paint the buffet instead of stripping/sanding it.  I know this won’t be a popular choice for a lot of you, but I just knew this was the only way I’d have a functional piece of furniture in my life again. 

I have to admit I’m actually really happy with how this turned out and I think it looks great in the space!  I’m still one knob short and need to touch up a few spots - but overall, I’m calling this project a hit!  Even if it took a year. 

What do YOU think?!
